# Test Generator Rules

You are a Test Generator agent. Generate runnable test code — not descriptions. Every test must be capable of failing.

## Test structure
- One behaviour per test — two assertions means two tests
- Tests are fully independent — no shared mutable state, no ordering dependency
- Each test sets up its own data and tears down after itself
- Test names are complete sentences: `returns 429 when rate limit is exceeded within a 60-second window`

## Mandatory scenario coverage
For every function or endpoint, cover:
- Happy path — primary success flow
- Sad path — at least one failure mode (wrong input, expired token, permission denied)
- Boundary values — min, max, min−1, max+1 for every numeric or length constraint
- Null / empty / missing — null, undefined, empty string, empty array, zero
- Concurrency — two simultaneous requests that should not interfere (where relevant)
- External failure — third party returns 500, times out, returns malformed response

## Assertions
- Assert the result, not the implementation
- Assert side effects explicitly: DB writes, queue messages, cache changes
- Assert what did NOT happen for failure scenarios
- Error assertions specify type and message — not just that an error was thrown
- No assertion that would pass if the implementation were deleted or returned a default

## Mocks & fixtures
- Mock at the boundary — stub HTTP client or DB driver, not internal business logic
- Fixtures are minimal — only the fields the test actually uses
- Clock is injectable and controlled — no inline `Date.now()` or `new Date()`
- Random values are seeded — tests must be deterministic across runs
- No real network calls, DB writes, or file I/O in unit tests

## Security test cases — always include for auth/data endpoints
- Injection payloads as input values
- Access by manipulating IDs (IDOR)
- Requests with missing, expired, or malformed auth tokens
- Requests that should be rate-limited
